1
00:01:11,000 --> 00:01:15,943
Medford City Council Committee of the Whole, June 23rd, 2026 is called to order.

2
00:01:16,563 --> 00:01:18,164
Mr. Clerk, please call the roll.

3
00:01:21,385 --> 00:01:22,326
Councilor Kelly.

4
00:01:28,449 --> 00:01:29,250
Councilor Lemming.

5
00:01:30,030 --> 00:01:30,510
Present.

6
00:01:32,151 --> 00:01:32,992
Councilor Milling.

7
00:01:33,012 --> 00:01:33,152
Present.

8
00:01:35,133 --> 00:01:35,933
Councilor Scarpelli.

9
00:01:35,953 --> 00:01:36,113
Present.

10
00:01:37,714 --> 00:01:38,535
Councilor Singh.

11
00:01:38,855 --> 00:01:39,235
Present.

12
00:01:40,795 --> 00:01:41,656
Vice President Lazaro.

13
00:01:41,676 --> 00:01:41,856
Present.

14
00:01:43,077 --> 00:01:43,917
And President Behrs.

15
00:01:43,957 --> 00:01:45,578
Present, seven present, none absent.

16
00:01:45,598 --> 00:01:46,819
The meeting is called to order.

17
00:01:47,460 --> 00:01:54,685
Action discussion items two, five, one, four, nine offered by council President Behrs resolution to establish a recruitment and hiring process for the city clerk.

18
00:01:55,165 --> 00:01:56,946
Final interview for council appointment.

19
00:01:57,527 --> 00:02:04,372
Be it resolved that the city council will hold final interviews for the two finalists for the position of city clerk of the city of Medford in a committee of the whole meeting on June 23rd, 2026 at 6 p.m.

20
00:02:06,513 --> 00:02:09,135
The finalists are as follows, Kevin Foley, Laurel Siegel.

21
00:02:09,595 --> 00:02:14,658
The hiring process outlined in resolution 25149 as approved in 2025 is included below.

22
00:02:15,218 --> 00:02:21,721
And I'll recognize Councilor Callahan, who worked with Vice President Lazaro and Councilor Mullane on this process.

23
00:02:22,262 --> 00:02:23,602
And then we will move to the candidates.

24
00:02:23,642 --> 00:02:24,323
Councilor Callahan.

25
00:02:25,533 --> 00:02:26,054
Thank you so much.

26
00:02:26,814 --> 00:02:33,521
We are excited to be in this process and to have a new clerk, a new city clerk.

27
00:02:34,602 --> 00:02:45,473
And also very appreciative of the two candidates for doing what we are mandated by the state to do, which is to hold this final interview in a public meeting.

28
00:02:46,154 --> 00:02:47,976
Not the norm for most HR decisions, but.

29
00:02:48,756 --> 00:03:06,752
That is that is as it is So I don't think there's any other real background information that we need I think for the public listening in we have been without a city clerk for a number of months and so we've been in a hiring process and if we've already had a number of

30
00:03:07,212 --> 00:03:13,555
interviews and both of these candidates have done multiple interviews with us and city staff as well, with the subcommittee.

31
00:03:14,735 --> 00:03:16,116
And so this is the final interview.

32
00:03:17,096 --> 00:03:22,178
We have four questions that will be the same for each of the candidates.

33
00:03:22,318 --> 00:03:32,002
And then after those four questions, which they'll have about three minutes to answer each one, then city councilors will be able to ask whatever questions they like.

34
00:03:33,362 --> 00:03:35,183
And I believe we are starting with Kevin Foley.

35
00:03:37,465 --> 00:03:37,705
Great.

36
00:03:37,785 --> 00:03:42,348
Kevin, and I'll turn it over to you, Councillor Callaghan, for the questions.

37
00:03:46,510 --> 00:03:47,650
Is my microphone on?

38
00:03:51,713 --> 00:03:52,473
Thank you for being here.

39
00:03:53,587 --> 00:03:57,492
Thank you, President Beers, Vice President Lazaro, members of the council.

40
00:03:57,933 --> 00:03:58,734
Thank you very much.

41
00:03:58,754 --> 00:04:08,948
I appreciate your opportunity to meet with you, to discuss my interest in serving, to answer your questions about my interest in serving as the city clerk here.

42
00:04:11,984 --> 00:04:16,988
I'd be obviously I would be humbled and honored to be selected.

43
00:04:18,189 --> 00:04:26,696
But you have an important decision to make and no matter what happens I just want to let the council know that I wish you well.

44
00:04:26,756 --> 00:04:36,524
I just had an opportunity to spend a few minutes with Attorney Siegel who I think is a very strong candidate and you'd be well served having her serve as the city clerk as well.

45
00:04:36,604 --> 00:04:40,567
So I'm happy to answer your questions and then we'll go from there.

46
00:04:41,526 --> 00:04:41,966
Thanks so much.

47
00:04:42,006 --> 00:04:43,887
We are thrilled to have two great candidates.

48
00:04:45,108 --> 00:04:53,211
So the first question is, please explain how your background has prepared you to do the most important tasks that the city clerk has to do.

49
00:04:55,352 --> 00:05:04,316
Well, you know, the way I look at the position is the most important task of the city clerk is actually to serve.

50
00:05:06,417 --> 00:05:08,138
You're gonna, the ideal candidate,

51
00:05:09,158 --> 00:05:36,842
uh... for all of you would be someone who's prepared to provide a high level of service to the city council to the uh... city of medford the community uh... to other departments here in city hall and others that are seeking either records or service from the city clerks office and so that level of service that ability to serve public service is is very important and as you can see from my background i have

52
00:05:37,502 --> 00:05:40,745
a strong commitment to public service.

53
00:05:40,825 --> 00:05:50,753
I think about 50 percent of my professional career has been spent in public service and well aware of those demands.

54
00:05:51,293 --> 00:05:52,895
I served as an elected official

55
00:05:55,217 --> 00:06:02,768
like all of you in my community in North Andover, a member of the select board, chairman of the select board.

56
00:06:03,369 --> 00:06:08,377
So I know full well what it means to rely upon staff.

57
00:06:09,279 --> 00:06:19,946
to keep you organized, to prepare your agenda, to prepare your business meetings, to keep records of those things, to keep time frames involved.

58
00:06:20,366 --> 00:06:23,908
And I know what it's like to do that work.

59
00:06:24,328 --> 00:06:25,029
It's very important.

60
00:06:25,049 --> 00:06:26,430
I also served as an appointed.

61
00:06:27,250 --> 00:06:38,675
official in North Andover, on the Conservation Commission, on the Strategic Planning Committee, on the Finance Committee most recently, and many other ad hoc committees.

62
00:06:39,475 --> 00:06:48,518
And so in that process, I certainly had the opportunity to be involved with many meetings and hearings.

63
00:06:49,219 --> 00:06:50,999
And I know what it takes.

64
00:06:53,056 --> 00:07:09,707
to prepare to make those meetings successful, the behind-the-scenes work, and I'm looking at Acting Clerk Alessio when I say that, to make those meetings go well, all the work behind the scenes that sometimes the public doesn't see and appreciate to make those meetings effective.

65
00:07:09,767 --> 00:07:12,970
I understand what that means, all that work.

66
00:07:13,310 --> 00:07:17,373
On the other hand, I also spent a considerable amount of time in the private sector.

67
00:07:17,973 --> 00:07:24,379
So on the other side of things, I did a lot of, I was a general practitioner, which is kind of like a dinosaur, because I did a lot of different things.

68
00:07:24,879 --> 00:07:32,746
I went in front of boards and commissions, conservation, planning, you know, board of selectmen, city council, for various items.

69
00:07:33,887 --> 00:07:44,016
And there are many times, not many times, but there are sometimes when you're in those meetings where, you know, there are some things, those meetings didn't go that well.

70
00:07:45,190 --> 00:07:56,459
It was evident that that preparation wasn't done in advance because there were items on that agenda that probably shouldn't have been on that agenda because they weren't ready to be on the agenda because things were missing.

71
00:07:57,019 --> 00:08:00,321
And, you know, now we're just taking up people's time and everything else.

72
00:08:00,341 --> 00:08:07,667
So I understand, you know, what it means to be, to make sure it's effective in terms of the council.

73
00:08:07,687 --> 00:08:11,230
Those are some of the things that I look at on how I would serve the council.

74
00:08:12,557 --> 00:08:14,278
making sure that you're organized.

75
00:08:14,678 --> 00:08:17,499
You know, the bottom line is I understand what it means.

76
00:08:17,979 --> 00:08:26,423
In terms of serving the public, like I think I mentioned this in the interviews, I look at the position as really kind of like an ambassador.

77
00:08:26,543 --> 00:08:32,285
Other than the mayor and the city council and some of the other officials, there's a lot of interaction with the community.

78
00:08:33,043 --> 00:08:39,248
People come up to that counter and they expect to be sure if you are the face of that clerk's office.

79
00:08:39,288 --> 00:08:46,673
And I really think if you want a clerk that's just going to go sit in the corner in the office and not interact with the public, I'm not your person because I expect I'll be out in the counter.

80
00:08:46,713 --> 00:08:51,477
I think I mentioned during one of the interviews, I used to be a staff attorney for Secretary Galvin.

81
00:08:52,738 --> 00:08:56,301
And they had a counter on the 17th floor, and there was a bullpen.

82
00:08:56,341 --> 00:08:57,962
And they said, Attorney Foley, we have an office for you.

83
00:08:58,002 --> 00:08:59,644
And I said, no, I want to sit here right in the bullpen.

84
00:09:00,144 --> 00:09:04,008
Because I'm very, I like to be able to go out and talk with people.

85
00:09:04,028 --> 00:09:07,551
I think I mentioned it the first time I met Counselor Melanchia.

86
00:09:07,591 --> 00:09:10,354
I met you before when I came into the law department.

87
00:09:10,394 --> 00:09:11,295
You notarized my.

88
00:09:11,895 --> 00:09:15,277
you notarized my nomination papers, and I said, well, was I nice to you?

89
00:09:15,297 --> 00:09:16,678
She said, yes, you were.

90
00:09:17,078 --> 00:09:18,619
And I think that's a part of the job.

91
00:09:18,679 --> 00:09:25,523
It's the face of the community, whether it's a resident or another department, and how we interact with them.

92
00:09:25,583 --> 00:09:34,288
So I'm someone that really is well-equipped to interact with the public, to work alongside

93
00:09:35,559 --> 00:09:43,904
the capable staff in the office to make sure that people that are coming to the city clerk's office seeking records or services are well served.

94
00:09:45,725 --> 00:09:46,325
Thank you so much.

95
00:09:48,527 --> 00:09:56,912
The second question is what do you think are the most pressing issues to be addressed by the new city clerk here in Medford and how would you address them?

96
00:09:57,872 --> 00:10:00,154
It's such a good question.

97
00:10:00,934 --> 00:10:02,095
I don't presume to know.

98
00:10:03,214 --> 00:10:05,016
what the most pressing issues are.

99
00:10:05,056 --> 00:10:20,130
I think I would be looking to the council, I'd be looking to the existing staff who've been there, I'd be looking to the consultant who's been there for eight or nine months, Andy, to sort of see what they have seen and what they think the needs are.

100
00:10:21,371 --> 00:10:27,317
My observations go back to more than a year when I was here as city solicitor and I think that we have to have our

101
00:10:28,576 --> 00:10:42,685
our paper records and our electronic records organized so that someone should be able to go on to the city website and be able to access the most recent revised version of our ordinances.

102
00:10:42,765 --> 00:10:44,226
Anybody should be able to get that.

103
00:10:44,246 --> 00:10:50,030
At the same time, they should be able to go on and get a history of what state statutes this body has adopted.

104
00:10:50,750 --> 00:10:51,871
and make sure those things are there.

105
00:10:51,891 --> 00:11:08,504
In terms of the paper records, I listened with interest to Acting Clerk Alessio's presentation during the budget hearings about the so-called vault project, $120,000 to put a new racking system in the vault in the clerk's office.

106
00:11:09,485 --> 00:11:16,670
And I think that's a great idea, because then you can get some of those historic records that are in the basement here at City Hall out of the basement.

107
00:11:17,371 --> 00:11:17,911
That's a must.

108
00:11:18,967 --> 00:11:19,527
in my opinion.

109
00:11:19,547 --> 00:11:34,334
At the same time, I was happy to hear that you have some of the applications on CitizenServe, and you have a part-time person who works part-time with the building department, part-time with the city clerk's office, who kind of oversees that stuff.

110
00:11:34,374 --> 00:11:43,698
That's leveraging other resources that you have, because one of the pressing issues that the city clerk's office, like the City of Medford has, is trying to do more with less.

111
00:11:43,798 --> 00:11:44,758
And so how can you do that?

112
00:11:44,778 --> 00:11:48,340
You do it with technology, you do it with resources, you do it with personnel.

113
00:11:48,860 --> 00:11:52,023
You work together to try to help solve a problem.

114
00:11:52,463 --> 00:11:54,305
So those are some of the things that I think that I

115
00:11:55,767 --> 00:11:57,229
I think are the most pressing issues.

116
00:11:58,810 --> 00:12:07,758
I also think that, you know, we can also build on some of that progress because, you know, not in a vacuum, but you look at some of the best practices.

117
00:12:08,358 --> 00:12:11,501
You know, what are some of the other communities doing?

118
00:12:12,182 --> 00:12:18,828
I know it's not as active as the City Solicitors Association, but the Clerks Association, what are they coming up with for best practices?

119
00:12:18,868 --> 00:12:20,769
I don't know what they came up with.

120
00:12:21,890 --> 00:12:24,212
down the Cape last week when they had their conference.

121
00:12:24,232 --> 00:12:26,674
But I know many city clerks in other communities.

122
00:12:27,074 --> 00:12:28,896
I'd probably want to know what they're thinking.

123
00:12:28,956 --> 00:12:37,142
I'd want to know what the council thinks and what the people, most importantly, that work in the office on a daily basis think about what the pressing issues are and how to resolve them.

124
00:12:39,965 --> 00:12:40,245
Thank you.

125
00:12:43,319 --> 00:12:51,388
The next question, please tell us about a time that you helped a team modernize and or adopt new policies in order to do their work better.

126
00:12:51,848 --> 00:12:56,253
I'll give you the short version first, which is a recent version, a very small scale version.

127
00:12:57,295 --> 00:12:59,197
The first week I was here as city solicitor,

128
00:13:01,097 --> 00:13:06,579
the public records requests were all going to an individual's email, Janet Spencer, who worked in the law department.

129
00:13:07,020 --> 00:13:09,401
And I couldn't understand why that was the case.

130
00:13:10,161 --> 00:13:16,203
And so the first week I was here, I asked our IT director, could we have a dedicated email for public records requests, please?

131
00:13:16,764 --> 00:13:23,807
And then we developed a form that was an acknowledgment of that records request, and we gave it a number.

132
00:13:24,807 --> 00:13:27,129
a FOIA number so that we could track it.

133
00:13:27,569 --> 00:13:37,437
So if someone called up and wanted to know the progress about a thing, and then same with the department heads, because you're going to send those requests out to the various departments that actually have the records most recently.

134
00:13:38,238 --> 00:13:44,763
I mean, most of the time it was the building department and other departments that were frequent records requests that were made.

135
00:13:45,223 --> 00:13:47,905
So they could go by a number, you know, and you could track it easier.

136
00:13:50,074 --> 00:13:56,859
As you can see from my resume, the larger and longer answer is I ran a professional corporation for 17 years.

137
00:13:58,260 --> 00:14:00,301
I was the sole shareholder.

138
00:14:00,882 --> 00:14:05,625
But I took over a general practice somewhere around 2012 or 13.

139
00:14:06,626 --> 00:14:09,268
And that practice did some things that I didn't always do.

140
00:14:09,348 --> 00:14:10,449
They did bank work.

141
00:14:10,489 --> 00:14:12,910
They did some probating estates and things like that.

142
00:14:13,171 --> 00:14:15,652
But everything they did was on paper.

143
00:14:16,333 --> 00:14:17,894
They were doing payroll on paper.

144
00:14:18,418 --> 00:14:20,140
They were keeping their files on paper.

145
00:14:20,560 --> 00:14:22,682
They were using paper forms.

146
00:14:22,722 --> 00:14:27,047
They were paper messages, paper calendar, paper, paper, paper.

147
00:14:27,127 --> 00:14:31,631
And the paralegal who had been there for 30 years, that's what she was used to doing.

148
00:14:34,394 --> 00:14:35,795
It really wasn't that effective.

149
00:14:35,815 --> 00:14:40,717
The equipment, some of the equipment, I think, that she was using probably came over on the Mayflower.

150
00:14:41,297 --> 00:14:46,240
She was single feeding a page at a time into the fax machine, into the scanner.

151
00:14:47,160 --> 00:14:53,243
So some of what I did was, I was an S corp, so I took the pain every two weeks when I did payroll.

152
00:14:53,844 --> 00:14:55,605
And I used a payroll company.

153
00:14:56,245 --> 00:14:57,545
And I also used QuickBooks.

154
00:14:57,626 --> 00:14:59,887
I had a QuickBooks consultant that came in.

155
00:15:00,847 --> 00:15:03,048
And she could tie into my system quarterly.

156
00:15:04,208 --> 00:15:11,450
At one time, I was handling $35 million a year through my little law firm.

157
00:15:12,131 --> 00:15:14,671
But we were always balanced to the penny.

158
00:15:14,751 --> 00:15:18,412
In fact, it was so balanced that at the end of the year, we'd give a little

159
00:15:22,815 --> 00:15:26,659
electronic file over to my accountant and my taxes were done the first week in February.

160
00:15:27,199 --> 00:15:30,382
That's very early for a corporation to have that stuff done.

161
00:15:30,922 --> 00:15:35,847
But we institute a lot of changes there in terms of equipment, four-in-one machines.

162
00:15:37,387 --> 00:15:50,191
You know, using QuickBooks, going, using a payroll company, direct deposit, paperless, bringing in new software for closings, bringing in new forms, electronic forms that you use at the probate court.

163
00:15:50,711 --> 00:16:02,415
And there was a bit of a learning curve with that, I must say, because as I said, my paralegal was someone who was a bit old school, used paper calendars, was really a little bit nervous about it, but after a while,

164
00:16:03,403 --> 00:16:06,044
It really was something that really worked out well.

165
00:16:06,064 --> 00:16:09,425
It made us more effective, more efficient, and everything else.

166
00:16:09,465 --> 00:16:12,126
So I look at that example of what I did there.

167
00:16:12,206 --> 00:16:13,286
And it was pleasant.

168
00:16:13,366 --> 00:16:14,146
She stayed with me.

169
00:16:14,246 --> 00:16:18,068
She didn't give up and quit, even though there was a lot of changes for how she did her work.

170
00:16:18,588 --> 00:16:25,870
And it was different than when someone had a question about a file and said, I'll have to call you back.

171
00:16:26,010 --> 00:16:29,311
I've got to run down to the basement and check, and I'll call you back.

172
00:16:29,571 --> 00:16:32,552
Because we would have everything electronically and get an answer to the question.

173
00:16:33,786 --> 00:16:34,186
Wonderful.

174
00:16:34,206 --> 00:16:34,827
Thank you so much.

175
00:16:35,968 --> 00:16:38,450
Trying to keep us on time here.

176
00:16:39,050 --> 00:16:47,137
How would you keep all the staff in the clerk's office properly trained in their jobs and knowledgeable about changing state laws and compliance regulations?

177
00:16:47,918 --> 00:16:52,781
That's another one where I don't want to presume that I know what the training needs.

178
00:16:54,025 --> 00:16:58,067
for the staff, the existing staff, and the office.

179
00:16:59,147 --> 00:17:02,769
For me, I would need to make an assessment.

180
00:17:03,109 --> 00:17:09,191
But I would probably ask the staff to give me a self-assessment about what we think the training needs are.

181
00:17:09,211 --> 00:17:13,613
And I'd also get some input from the council if there's some issue.

182
00:17:13,913 --> 00:17:16,454
And the consultant that's been there for nine months now.

183
00:17:16,975 --> 00:17:21,777
He's an objective third party that really I'm sure that I would want to

184
00:17:23,676 --> 00:17:36,282
spend some time about what if any recommendations after serving in there for 20 hours a week for nine months, what do you see in terms of needs for training and stuff like that.

185
00:17:36,322 --> 00:17:38,162
So that's how I would go about it.

186
00:17:38,222 --> 00:17:39,363
Some of that's a self-assessment.

187
00:17:39,383 --> 00:17:41,564
And then in terms of the training itself,

188
00:17:42,664 --> 00:17:43,945
You know, what's accessible?

189
00:17:43,985 --> 00:17:48,028
Is it something that we can handle within the confines of City Hall?

190
00:17:48,048 --> 00:17:49,509
Do we have to go to an outside vendor?

191
00:17:49,829 --> 00:17:58,855
If we go to an outside vendor, can that training be taken remotely here at City Hall, or do we have to send somebody off-site, which means, you know, juggling the schedule?

192
00:17:59,315 --> 00:18:01,177
Or is it something that we could send one person?

193
00:18:01,961 --> 00:18:06,544
to go and get trained and then come back to the office and they could embark that training on all of us.

194
00:18:06,664 --> 00:18:13,628
It's all sort of fact dependent, but that's the way I would look at assessing and implementing the training for staff there.

195
00:18:14,268 --> 00:18:17,030
Of course, you know, I should mention my background.

196
00:18:19,162 --> 00:18:28,644
For 24 years, I've been an adjunct professor of law at the Mass School of Law, and I also did a stint out at Dean College in their baccalaureate program for undergraduates.

197
00:18:28,704 --> 00:18:32,625
So I'm not afraid to train as long as I'm properly trained.

198
00:18:33,125 --> 00:18:35,326
I'm happy to help with the training.

199
00:18:36,066 --> 00:18:40,507
Oh, part two of that I don't think I answered, which was keeping the staff updated on

200
00:18:41,850 --> 00:18:45,531
Keeping the staff updated on current changes to the law, isn't that part of the question?

201
00:18:45,551 --> 00:18:45,931
That's right.

202
00:18:46,271 --> 00:18:47,491
And regulations and stuff like that.

203
00:18:47,511 --> 00:18:50,392
I think that's something that would primarily fall upon me.

204
00:18:50,452 --> 00:18:51,272
And how do you do it?

205
00:18:51,652 --> 00:18:54,793
Well, I think you've got to have regular staff meetings.

206
00:18:54,833 --> 00:18:57,414
Let them know the trends or what's going on.

207
00:18:58,174 --> 00:19:06,116
Sometimes, depending on what that change is or if it's going to change the way we do business, it might mean a memorandum or it might mean a directive, a written directive.

208
00:19:06,396 --> 00:19:08,077
From now on, we're going to do it this way.

209
00:19:08,097 --> 00:19:09,177
So that's the way I would handle that.

210
00:19:10,477 --> 00:19:10,937
Fantastic.

211
00:19:10,957 --> 00:19:11,638
Thank you so much.

212
00:19:12,719 --> 00:19:15,481
I'll turn it back over to Council President Burris.

213
00:19:16,001 --> 00:19:18,142
Thank you, Councilor Callahan.

214
00:19:18,162 --> 00:19:20,584
Thank you, Kevin, for answering those questions.

215
00:19:20,624 --> 00:19:26,368
Do we have any follow-up questions or additional questions from members of the council for Attorney Foley?

216
00:19:33,593 --> 00:19:34,334
I'm seeing none.

217
00:19:34,354 --> 00:19:36,335
All right.

218
00:19:37,271 --> 00:19:37,792
Thank you, Kevin.

219
00:19:37,852 --> 00:19:38,612
Thank you for your time.

220
00:19:38,732 --> 00:19:39,713
Wishing the council well.

221
00:19:39,733 --> 00:19:41,935
Wish you the best with whatever you decide to do.

222
00:19:42,196 --> 00:19:42,916
Thank you very much.

223
00:19:42,936 --> 00:19:43,537
Take it easy.

224
00:20:08,862 --> 00:20:09,512
Ghost dog.

225
00:20:53,259 --> 00:20:54,920
Welcome, Attorney Segal.

226
00:20:55,801 --> 00:21:00,065
We are going to have kind of four standard questions.

227
00:21:00,125 --> 00:21:02,186
Counselor Callahan is going to run through them.

228
00:21:02,687 --> 00:21:06,790
And then if counselors have follow-up questions, we will ask you some follow-up questions.

229
00:21:08,091 --> 00:21:08,872
Counselor Callahan.

230
00:21:10,233 --> 00:21:10,633
Thank you.

231
00:21:11,294 --> 00:21:12,555
First of all, thank you for being here.

232
00:21:17,053 --> 00:21:18,775
Yeah, I didn't think it was on.

233
00:21:19,736 --> 00:21:21,078
Thank you so much for inviting me.

234
00:21:21,338 --> 00:21:21,538
Yes.

235
00:21:22,019 --> 00:21:22,539
Absolutely.

236
00:21:24,702 --> 00:21:33,672
So the first question is, if you could please explain how your background has prepared you to do the most important tasks that the city clerk has to do.

237
00:21:34,305 --> 00:21:34,465
Okay.

238
00:21:34,825 --> 00:21:37,147
Happy to do that.

239
00:21:37,247 --> 00:21:41,631
I believe, as all of you know, my previous career was as an attorney.

240
00:21:41,651 --> 00:21:47,295
I practiced law for about 30 years in real estate and business transactions.

241
00:21:47,755 --> 00:21:56,042
Of course, I do have a facility and knowledge of the law and an ability to research and understand and implement legal requirements.

242
00:21:57,844 --> 00:22:01,188
In addition to that, I've now worked on staff for three years.

243
00:22:02,029 --> 00:22:13,683
I am the CDBG manager and I manage federal funding and other funds for the city, which has extensive reporting records and financial requirements.

244
00:22:15,925 --> 00:22:18,807
I have a great deal of experience in managing those tasks.

245
00:22:20,368 --> 00:22:38,518
I'm also a long-time resident of this city and have served on a huge variety of nonprofit boards and committees as well as several other city commissions, the Parking Policy Commission, the Charter Study Committee, the Medford Arts Council.

246
00:22:39,618 --> 00:22:41,759
So I think I have a really good understanding

247
00:22:43,120 --> 00:22:52,392
city policy and needs because I can view it from all those different angles as both a resident and an employee and somebody who has worked extensively with the city.

248
00:22:53,933 --> 00:22:58,799
And last but certainly not least, I was the managing member of a five attorney law firm.

249
00:22:59,100 --> 00:23:00,401
So I know how to

250
00:23:01,862 --> 00:23:02,843
lead a team.

251
00:23:03,463 --> 00:23:07,044
I've also held leadership positions with a number of different non-profits.

252
00:23:08,205 --> 00:23:20,790
So, first of all, I have a lot of experience just digging in and getting the work done that needs to be done, but also know how to guide a team and motivate them towards the tasks that need to be accomplished.

253
00:23:22,538 --> 00:23:24,521
Thank you.

254
00:23:24,581 --> 00:23:31,673
Our second question, what do you think are the most pressing issues to be addressed by the new city clerk and how would you address them?

255
00:23:33,590 --> 00:23:45,458
I think an immediate priority is we know that there is some backlog that has accumulated on codifying city ordinances in part just due to gaps in staffing.

256
00:23:46,298 --> 00:24:02,509
So I think that that's a high priority to bring that back up to date and also look at perhaps further measures that we can take to ensure that there is less of a possibility of establishing a backlog in the future.

257
00:24:03,709 --> 00:24:17,357
I want to work with the council to ensure that there is clear and good communication back and forth and that there is clear tracking of any matters that are before the council.

258
00:24:20,282 --> 00:24:37,136
I think it's also very important to facilitate communication with other departments in the city, particularly where the matters that you are making decisions on impact their daily work and that they are aware of what is coming before you and also aware of whatever action has been taken on those matters.

259
00:24:40,347 --> 00:24:44,249
And I think also there's a lot of importance of continuing to modernize.

260
00:24:44,269 --> 00:24:56,914
There's been a lot of activity to move clerk duties onto online platforms, which is great, but as much as we can continue to move in that direction and make sure that we're maximizing the use of the technology.

261
00:24:56,934 --> 00:25:03,857
You know, we have a couple of great systems that we're using right now, the Civic Clerk System and CitizenServe.

262
00:25:04,257 --> 00:25:08,358
They have some additional functionality, so seeing how we can capitalize on those functions.

263
00:25:12,544 --> 00:25:16,727
And if there are other programs, I'm sorry.

264
00:25:16,907 --> 00:25:24,053
And one of the things actually that I've been working on a lot in PDS is ensuring that all materials are fully accessible to the public.

265
00:25:24,093 --> 00:25:31,678
The Commonwealth has actually recently established some new regulations on digital accessibility.

266
00:25:32,659 --> 00:25:34,680
The implementation of that was actually deferred.

267
00:25:34,700 --> 00:25:37,823
It was supposed to go into effect April of this year, but it's been deferred.

268
00:25:38,503 --> 00:25:43,127
But it's a real opportunity to make sure all of the materials through the clerk's office are complying with that.

269
00:25:43,187 --> 00:25:57,739
It's everything from, you know, using more clear language to visual standards to making sure that documents that are available are readable through accessible technology, all of that sort of stuff.

270
00:25:58,373 --> 00:26:01,494
Thank you, and I am gonna be trying to keep us to three minutes.

271
00:26:01,535 --> 00:26:02,675
Okay, sorry folks.

272
00:26:02,735 --> 00:26:07,297
No, no, he also, I forgot to time him on the first one, he definitely went over, so I was giving you this one.

273
00:26:08,518 --> 00:26:09,058
You each get one.

274
00:26:11,079 --> 00:26:19,083
Wonderful, our third question, please tell us about a time that you helped a team modernize and or adopt new policies in order to better do their work.

275
00:26:19,625 --> 00:26:20,545
Okay.

276
00:26:20,645 --> 00:26:24,767
I think really my role as the CDBG manager is the best example of that.

277
00:26:25,827 --> 00:26:35,751
You know, CDBG is a really complex area, and federal regulations are deep and ever evolving, particularly in the current atmosphere.

278
00:26:36,531 --> 00:26:42,673
And so I've done a lot of work to bring us into current compliance and make sure that we're tracking everything.

279
00:26:43,533 --> 00:26:48,175
So a couple of examples of that, you know, I set up a whole new financial system for

280
00:26:48,695 --> 00:26:53,923
managing CDBG funding and making sure that we're tracking all of our expenditures and funds coming back in.

281
00:26:55,064 --> 00:27:02,595
I've talked about this before, but actually Alicia Hunt, my director, liked the system so much that she's adopted it throughout the department.

282
00:27:05,537 --> 00:27:27,289
I created a new CDBG page on the city's website because really we were before just a little drop down on the PDS page and that really didn't provide adequate information to comply with the government requirements and also give the public more information about what CDBG is, what its intent and goals are and the various documents that are affiliated with that program.

283
00:27:28,650 --> 00:27:37,136
I also rewrote our CDBG citizen participation plan, which is the guiding document for how we engage with the public about our CDBG funding.

284
00:27:37,697 --> 00:27:43,181
What we had was outdated, not up to date with the current requirements, and also pretty unclear.

285
00:27:45,722 --> 00:28:05,186
And I implemented a new software program to manage our CDBG grants to our public services grantees, which really facilitates their better management of the grant, better reporting, and also allows them to see in real time the status of their expenditures and funding for the program.

286
00:28:05,806 --> 00:28:12,528
And last but not least, I worked with staff to establish new CDBG funded programs, programs like our rehab

287
00:28:13,768 --> 00:28:14,648
loan program.

288
00:28:15,529 --> 00:28:27,212
We just closed on the very first loan under that new revived program last week, as well as some of the econ dev programs like the project pop-up and the vacant storefront grants that we've been doing.

289
00:28:27,232 --> 00:28:29,193
Very good.

290
00:28:31,182 --> 00:28:31,502
All right.

291
00:28:31,943 --> 00:28:40,673
How would you keep all staff in the clerk's office properly trained in their jobs and knowledgeable about changing state laws and compliance regulations?

292
00:28:41,053 --> 00:28:41,293
Sure.

293
00:28:42,234 --> 00:28:45,979
So, you know, as I said, I'm very familiar with staying abreast of what's going on in the law.

294
00:28:46,779 --> 00:28:55,385
I think the first thing is to make sure that I'm fully informed of what all of those requirements are and also what educational opportunities exist.

295
00:28:55,845 --> 00:29:05,571
I know that there are municipal clerk associations and other groups and also just talking with colleagues from other communities to really understand what they're doing.

296
00:29:06,791 --> 00:29:12,335
And then I want to meet with the staff individually and get their thoughts.

297
00:29:12,635 --> 00:29:13,575
You know, where are they?

298
00:29:13,635 --> 00:29:14,335
What do they know?

299
00:29:14,635 --> 00:29:15,536
What do they want to know?

300
00:29:16,976 --> 00:29:23,517
Where do they see the gaps in the office and what needs to be learned in order to function more appropriately?

301
00:29:23,537 --> 00:29:29,378
I do understand that there has actually been quite a bit of desire for additional training by some of the staff.

302
00:29:29,818 --> 00:29:35,419
But again, there's been struggles because there have been gaps in staffing and other obstacles that have made that difficult.

303
00:29:35,519 --> 00:29:39,580
So as much as I'm able to facilitate that happening for them, I want to do that.

304
00:29:43,492 --> 00:29:45,734
All right, those are our four standard questions.

305
00:29:46,134 --> 00:29:47,635
Back to you, President Behrs.

306
00:29:48,115 --> 00:29:49,196
Thank you, Councilor Callahan.

307
00:29:49,216 --> 00:29:50,177
Thank you, Attorney Segal.

308
00:29:50,577 --> 00:29:52,038
Do we have any follow-up questions?

309
00:29:53,900 --> 00:29:54,620
Councilor Scarpa?

310
00:29:55,601 --> 00:29:56,602
First of all, very impressive.

311
00:29:56,622 --> 00:29:57,422
Thank you.

312
00:29:57,442 --> 00:30:02,646
And for everything you've done in your existing role, it's very appreciated, I think.

313
00:30:02,846 --> 00:30:03,607
It's very impressive.

314
00:30:04,147 --> 00:30:11,513
My only question I have is, it's a little difficult, a little different, because you are here as a member of our staff.

315
00:30:12,632 --> 00:30:17,039
but joining as the clerk, there is a separation, right?

316
00:30:18,341 --> 00:30:26,533
And how do you think you handle the role knowing that you represent the council first, not the central administration?

317
00:30:28,022 --> 00:30:29,963
I mean, I don't see that as being problematic.

318
00:30:30,003 --> 00:30:35,004
That's, you know, whoever I report to, that's who I report to and the chain of command.

319
00:30:35,805 --> 00:30:39,686
So I don't, you know, I respect the work of the council.

320
00:30:39,786 --> 00:30:41,546
I respect the work of the administration.

321
00:30:42,787 --> 00:30:44,427
And so I don't see that as being problematic.

322
00:30:45,248 --> 00:30:45,528
Thank you.

323
00:30:48,068 --> 00:30:48,369
Thank you.

324
00:30:49,289 --> 00:30:51,770
Do we have any further follow-up questions?

325
00:30:55,391 --> 00:30:55,611
All right.

326
00:30:56,777 --> 00:30:58,078
Thank you, Laurel.

327
00:30:58,098 --> 00:31:00,140
Thank you, Attorney Segal.

328
00:31:01,321 --> 00:31:06,305
At this point, you know, we will go into kind of our deliberations.

329
00:31:07,947 --> 00:31:19,416
Procedurally, we would make a motion after our discussions to recommend a candidate, then engage in an offer process and negotiation.

330
00:31:21,058 --> 00:31:23,420
When that's completed, we would then have

331
00:31:24,133 --> 00:31:27,758
a vote to actually appoint someone as the city clerk.

332
00:31:28,198 --> 00:31:30,361
We can't appoint a city solicitor.

333
00:31:31,082 --> 00:31:35,647
So that is how this will go.

334
00:31:35,867 --> 00:31:39,892
So I will open it up to... Yep, that'd be great.

335
00:31:43,317 --> 00:31:43,477
Sure.

336
00:31:51,938 --> 00:31:54,200
You're gonna have to close the big one.

337
00:31:55,381 --> 00:31:55,661
Yeah.

338
00:31:59,344 --> 00:32:00,265
The door is broken.

339
00:32:05,089 --> 00:32:18,601
Sorry, just to recap, we will discuss now if we choose at this time to make a recommendation of one of the two finalists that we saw, then we would make an offer to that person

340
00:32:20,318 --> 00:32:27,119
And if that person were to accept that we would take a final vote to appoint them as the city clerk.

341
00:32:29,500 --> 00:32:31,120
I'll go to Councilor Callahan.

342
00:32:32,180 --> 00:32:32,441
Thank you.

343
00:32:32,521 --> 00:32:45,263
I just would hoping to ask like what the form of the motion is the form of the motion to offer the job or the form of the motion to if you don't mind.

344
00:32:46,457 --> 00:32:50,119
Sure, I mean, I think that's really, it's not like a specific one.

345
00:32:50,199 --> 00:32:50,719
Okay.

346
00:32:50,919 --> 00:32:54,861
Yeah, just a motion to recommend X candidate and make an offer.

347
00:32:55,301 --> 00:32:55,601
Great.

348
00:32:55,921 --> 00:32:56,081
Yeah.

349
00:32:56,521 --> 00:32:56,942
Thank you.

350
00:32:59,083 --> 00:33:00,323
Vice President Lazaro.

351
00:33:02,444 --> 00:33:08,947
First of all, I just want to acknowledge that this is not how anybody wants to do hiring.

352
00:33:10,730 --> 00:33:19,279
because it's very awkward, but it's how we're required to do it because we do things in a public forum.

353
00:33:19,619 --> 00:33:26,847
So we had to bring our final candidates here into a public meeting, but the rest of the process was more normal.

354
00:33:27,808 --> 00:33:31,472
We just interviewed people like you would normally interview people.

355
00:33:32,016 --> 00:33:36,098
narrowed down the candidates, and now we have this process here.

356
00:33:36,718 --> 00:34:00,288
So, both candidates are qualified and intelligent, and they have experience in Medford, and it's so hard to talk about personnel stuff publicly, but I would love for us to get the ball rolling, and since I have talked about

357
00:34:01,190 --> 00:34:02,851
candidates already.

358
00:34:02,871 --> 00:34:12,458
I just, my, I am leaning in the direction of,

359
00:34:16,529 --> 00:34:35,498
I think Laurel's experience lends itself more directly to this role because it is clerical and specifically related to regulations and frequently changing laws and keeping tabs of things like that.

360
00:34:35,518 --> 00:34:38,779
So that's my preference.

361
00:34:43,506 --> 00:34:49,087
But I would be interested to hear what the other counselors think.

362
00:34:49,708 --> 00:34:50,028
Thank you.

363
00:34:51,588 --> 00:34:51,948
Thank you.

364
00:34:51,968 --> 00:34:55,309
Councilor Scarpelli.

365
00:34:56,349 --> 00:35:02,511
So just to be clear we're in a public forum talking about personnel matters.

366
00:35:05,112 --> 00:35:06,292
I as one of I think.

367
00:35:07,033 --> 00:35:10,376
Council Beers, I think you were part of the last clerk, right?

368
00:35:10,476 --> 00:35:10,696
Were you?

369
00:35:10,916 --> 00:35:11,097
Was it?

370
00:35:11,897 --> 00:35:12,338
You were not.

371
00:35:12,398 --> 00:35:20,945
So being the only one, I don't know who has guided us to say this is the proper format because I think this is terrible.

372
00:35:22,827 --> 00:35:33,837
I think that truly to really understand is really for this council to understand that this person that we'll be hiring is working for us.

373
00:35:34,929 --> 00:35:47,373
and really having an open board discussion that you might want to say something but not be protected because we don't have a city solicitor to guide us and we don't have a legal team to guide us into this process.

374
00:35:48,134 --> 00:35:49,134
So I think it's flawed.

375
00:35:49,154 --> 00:35:52,495
I want to make that as a point of record.

376
00:35:53,115 --> 00:35:57,117
The fact that we're doing this this way is shocking.

377
00:35:57,497 --> 00:36:01,678
Now, on a personal level with the two candidates that we had, I think they're both phenomenal.

378
00:36:04,325 --> 00:36:10,029
I think our second candidate is phenomenal in the role that she's in right now.

379
00:36:10,689 --> 00:36:21,496
And I feel that that is more powerful and more impactful in our community for her to be in that role.

380
00:36:21,556 --> 00:36:24,898
I think we weaken our system by taking her out of that role.

381
00:36:25,738 --> 00:36:33,083
I think the first candidate has shown that he has worked in every single aspect that we find

382
00:36:33,902 --> 00:36:36,504
that we're lapsing in.

383
00:36:37,484 --> 00:36:44,609
And having both of them have a background with the legal system and legalities, I think it's very important.

384
00:36:44,649 --> 00:36:53,635
Although they can't give us a legal opinion, but it's nice to know that we have people in that role that have that background.

385
00:36:54,175 --> 00:36:56,817
So either way, I think it's a win-win.

386
00:36:57,477 --> 00:37:01,300
But, you know, the fact that

387
00:37:02,691 --> 00:37:08,979
When you look at the resumes and understand one against the other, they're both very talented.

388
00:37:09,099 --> 00:37:18,391
But I think for the position that we're looking in, I think Mr. Foley better fits that position for what he has done directly in that type of role.

389
00:37:19,312 --> 00:37:20,414
And that's why I would.

390
00:37:20,770 --> 00:37:23,031
lean more toward Mr. Foley.

391
00:37:24,231 --> 00:37:32,714
And I think that it's unfair, it's an unfair bias that I feel that moving Laurel into this position out of another position weakens us in a sense.

392
00:37:33,914 --> 00:37:36,095
We don't get stronger in that office by taking her out.

393
00:37:37,276 --> 00:37:50,560
So and I think that that's what's playing this, it's very difficult for me to weigh this because it is, it's, you're adding but subtracting with one person.

394
00:37:52,107 --> 00:37:54,269
And that's what makes it very difficult for me right now.

395
00:37:54,349 --> 00:38:00,353
But that's why I think my choice would have to be that it would be Attorney Foley.

396
00:38:01,174 --> 00:38:05,717
And the fact that he understands as well the system.

397
00:38:06,178 --> 00:38:08,119
He knows all the players.

398
00:38:08,199 --> 00:38:12,582
He understands both sides of the clerk's position in the office.

399
00:38:16,105 --> 00:38:27,114
You know, his ability to teach, his ability to work with a team, I think is very impressive, as well as Laurel.

400
00:38:27,134 --> 00:38:37,423
I think she's, you know, you've seen the transformation that she's made in that department, and it'd be interesting to see, it'd be exciting to see what she can do in the clerk's role as well.

401
00:38:37,883 --> 00:38:41,967
So this is why it's not easy, but like I said, the only piece that,

402
00:38:43,559 --> 00:38:57,415
that I'm hanging my hat on and saying that a subtraction in addition to the clerk would be a subtraction that would hurt our process, especially in probably one of the most important offices we have right now.

403
00:38:58,356 --> 00:39:00,118
So thank you for listening.

404
00:39:00,138 --> 00:39:01,239
Thank you, Councilor Scarpelli.

405
00:39:01,279 --> 00:39:02,140
Councilor Callahan.

406
00:39:03,782 --> 00:39:04,042
Thank you.

407
00:39:05,455 --> 00:39:11,880
I want to reiterate what my colleagues have said, which is that both of these candidates are excellent.

408
00:39:11,960 --> 00:39:15,763
I'm so thrilled that we are at this point in the process.

409
00:39:15,823 --> 00:39:24,409
I'm very excited to have a new city clerk, and I also think that this format is quite

410
00:39:26,170 --> 00:39:26,790
uncomfortable.

411
00:39:28,712 --> 00:39:46,563
And that being said, I also, like from my perspective, I have, and I think most of us on the city council, have had the opportunity to interact with both of these people in their respective roles with the city.

412
00:39:47,723 --> 00:40:03,512
And I think between this interview, I was on the committee that did the earlier interviews, and our own personal sort of interactions and our own knowledge of working with

413
00:40:04,632 --> 00:40:12,636
I personally feel comfortable just making that decision for myself and also other councils if they, you know, wish.

414
00:40:13,296 --> 00:40:23,261
I just want to leave the door open for people to feel that they don't have to necessarily say the reason for their vote before they vote.

415
00:40:26,082 --> 00:40:27,604
I'm not going to, I think they're both wonderful.

416
00:40:28,265 --> 00:40:29,106
I have to choose one.

417
00:40:29,126 --> 00:40:31,588
I think either one would be fantastic.

418
00:40:33,510 --> 00:40:34,912
So that's all I have to say.

419
00:40:34,932 --> 00:40:35,312
Thank you.

420
00:40:36,453 --> 00:40:38,475
Thank you, Councilor Lemming and Councilor Malay.

421
00:40:41,619 --> 00:40:42,019
Thank you.

422
00:40:43,712 --> 00:40:54,695
Yeah, I echoing everything else my colleagues have said that, yeah, this is definitely not the ideal forum or format for this.

423
00:40:55,235 --> 00:41:05,518
And also echoing that, being familiar with the work of both of the candidates, I'm deeply impressed with both of them.

424
00:41:05,578 --> 00:41:07,779
And just thank both of them for putting their candidacy

425
00:41:10,447 --> 00:41:10,828
ahead.

426
00:41:12,228 --> 00:41:23,355
I'll say that for me personally, I'm sort of a one, when it comes to the clerk's office, the main focus of mine is getting through the ordinance backlog.

427
00:41:24,996 --> 00:41:34,201
And I mean, that's just something that has been holding up the clerk's office and the update of Munich code for a long time.

428
00:41:34,261 --> 00:41:35,622
And so I'll be

429
00:41:36,407 --> 00:41:42,072
you know, I was kind of keeping my ears open during the interviews for which candidates would say that.

430
00:41:43,433 --> 00:41:56,804
And, you know, that's, that is, I'm sort of a single issue counselor in terms of how I'll be voting tonight, but, but yeah, that's, that's, that's the basis of my decision.

431
00:41:56,984 --> 00:41:57,304
Thank you.

432
00:41:57,324 --> 00:42:00,447
I think Councilor Lemming, Councilor Malayne.

433
00:42:03,617 --> 00:42:13,166
So, I would also echo what everyone has said, that this is, you know, a very kind of uncomfortable format to be doing this and having these discussions.

434
00:42:14,227 --> 00:42:20,072
Again, I think both candidates bring very unique kind of perspectives and abilities to the same role.

435
00:42:20,933 --> 00:42:40,450
I think what I, in terms of my vote and what I was looking for and listening to as part of this process, the things that really stood out to me is kind of that attention to detail, organizational, you know, focus, because I do think a lot of that is important within this position.

436
00:42:41,310 --> 00:42:54,214
And someone who was able to demonstrate and give some examples when it comes to how they would move the office forward around technology and really embracing that and how we might be able to

437
00:42:56,555 --> 00:43:01,036
be able to catch up on some of these areas and issues that have been brought up in the past.

438
00:43:01,556 --> 00:43:16,999
And I think that in listening to both candidates, I was listening for exact examples and where they have demonstrated making an impact in some of those, and I think one of the candidates really did kind of lean into that more.

439
00:43:17,199 --> 00:43:21,120
And I like to hear exact examples where someone has done this in the past and

440
00:43:21,520 --> 00:43:26,422
and utilize that within different types of systems and be able to navigate that successfully.

441
00:43:26,442 --> 00:43:39,328
Again, both bring very unique, wonderful skill sets to it, but I think when I make my decision as well, that's what I'm leaning towards, the person that really provided more of those direct examples.

442
00:43:43,550 --> 00:43:45,351
Thank you, Councillor Mullen, Councillor Hussain.

443
00:43:46,709 --> 00:43:49,091
Thank you, Councilor Behrs, Council President Behrs.

444
00:43:50,152 --> 00:43:54,495
I want to thank both candidates for coming in front of the public tonight.

445
00:43:54,595 --> 00:44:03,883
It's not easy to put yourself in front of a live cast and to have a very public and awkward job interview.

446
00:44:05,852 --> 00:44:14,117
I also want to thank both candidates on top of that for being willing to serve in this capacity, to serve the council, to serve the city and our residents.

447
00:44:14,798 --> 00:44:24,063
I think we've seen two pretty impressive applications tonight, two pretty well-spoken interviews as well.

448
00:44:25,164 --> 00:44:29,227
And I think despite the hiccups in the process,

449
00:44:31,612 --> 00:44:44,240
I want to thank the three counselors here, Counselor Callahan, Lazaro, and Mullane for their work serving on the subcommittee that's gotten us to this point and gotten us two very strong candidates in front of us.

450
00:44:45,901 --> 00:44:56,487
As I've reviewed the materials that we were handed, the interviews that we heard tonight, I've been thinking a lot about what the role really demands.

451
00:44:58,850 --> 00:45:04,233
When I think of the city clerk's office, I think of it as a connective tissue in city government.

452
00:45:05,094 --> 00:45:11,998
It's responsible for public records and touches licensing, meeting minutes in the council, of course.

453
00:45:13,899 --> 00:45:23,625
It's about transparency too and it's about knowing what residents want and need from the city and want to know and need to know from the city as well.

454
00:45:24,666 --> 00:45:27,648
And so, you know, I think,

455
00:45:28,623 --> 00:45:32,045
Both candidates talked about their legal experience and administrative experience.

456
00:45:32,085 --> 00:45:33,505
I think it's a bit more than that.

457
00:45:33,905 --> 00:45:36,887
I think it's also about institutional knowledge.

458
00:45:37,007 --> 00:45:57,756
It's about community trust and connection to the community knowing the perspectives of the stakeholders who come to City Hall for help and knowing the shortfalls of those interactions thus far and improving those interactions so that things run smoother for our residents.

459
00:45:59,488 --> 00:46:12,877
Our city clerk serves everyone and I think it's a difficult decision because, you know, it's not unlike other departments.

460
00:46:12,937 --> 00:46:15,159
It's one that we have control over.

461
00:46:15,279 --> 00:46:23,365
It's one that we have a say in the process in and it's important nowadays and especially

462
00:46:24,030 --> 00:46:29,712
to have that kind of experience divorced from the central administration too.

463
00:46:30,392 --> 00:46:32,653
So this is a difficult choice.

464
00:46:33,333 --> 00:46:47,278
I think a lot about that community, for me it just comes back to that question of community connection and the, and knowing what it's like to be on the other side of the counter when they walk into the city clerk's office.

465
00:46:48,218 --> 00:46:49,919
So that's what I'm going to be thinking about tonight.

466
00:46:57,076 --> 00:47:06,230
Is there any further discussion by members of the council regarding our recommendation for making an offer to a city clerk?

467
00:47:10,336 --> 00:47:10,537
All right.

468
00:47:11,797 --> 00:47:14,238
Seeing none, I just want to thank my fellow councilors.

469
00:47:14,278 --> 00:47:17,980
I understand the qualms with the process.

470
00:47:18,220 --> 00:47:25,204
Whenever an employee is hired by a public body, that public body is subject to the open meeting law.

471
00:47:25,744 --> 00:47:32,728
And we have to take our votes and have a discussion in public to make a recommendation.

472
00:47:32,808 --> 00:47:38,531
And, you know, there are other parts of the process obviously that happen.

473
00:47:39,290 --> 00:47:43,832
in a bit of a different way, but when it gets to this final stage, the last part, there is a public vote.

474
00:47:44,372 --> 00:47:53,035
You know, people have to decide who they want to vote for, and then it moves ahead from that point.

475
00:47:53,715 --> 00:47:59,157
So, you know, there are a few different ways that we could go about it.

476
00:47:59,277 --> 00:48:03,339
I think something that might be

477
00:48:04,028 --> 00:48:16,001
The best way to do it would be for each of us to maybe someone make a motion to recommend a city clerk and then each of us could say the name of a finalist and that way no one has to vote yes or no on anybody.

478
00:48:16,281 --> 00:48:21,907
They just say the name of the finalist that they want to make the offer to and whoever has the most.

479
00:48:23,558 --> 00:48:25,359
Names said it will go from there.

480
00:48:26,499 --> 00:48:33,743
I believe I looked back at the 2018 process and I believe that's how they did it on the council at that time.

481
00:48:34,863 --> 00:48:35,763
No, George?

482
00:48:36,484 --> 00:48:36,844
What did you do?

483
00:48:49,217 --> 00:48:57,082
The way we decided in executive session that we would talk and vet out each candidate in an executive session, sharing information.

484
00:48:57,723 --> 00:49:07,790
And then after we all expressed our feelings and understandings, we then decided that whatever we left, we left.

485
00:49:08,511 --> 00:49:10,592
making sure that we're unanimous in the decision.

486
00:49:11,072 --> 00:49:31,621
So we knew ahead of time, after we've entered the process as a team, that when we left, we left knowing that even though I might have favored one applicant over another, that after the group decided that we left as a unified front and making sure the person that we brought in to sit in that seat, that they knew they had seven people that they could depend on.

487
00:49:31,641 --> 00:49:32,081
So.

488
00:49:37,335 --> 00:49:41,642
The advice of council that we received is that that wasn't an option for us here.

489
00:49:41,662 --> 00:49:41,702
So.

490
00:49:49,838 --> 00:49:50,799
very difficult times.

491
00:49:51,059 --> 00:49:57,503
And I think that our city councils, my colleagues did an amazing job vetting a very difficult process.

492
00:49:57,523 --> 00:50:07,210
Because one thing we were purview to is the process coming from our HR department and understanding how the process went.

493
00:50:07,270 --> 00:50:14,695
And to me, void of a city solicitor where my colleagues could have gone to at any time to say, is this the process?

494
00:50:15,516 --> 00:50:16,497
Is there other ways?

495
00:50:17,600 --> 00:50:18,784
And we don't have that.

496
00:50:18,804 --> 00:50:20,109
So here we are.

497
00:50:20,530 --> 00:50:23,260
We need a city clerk, but we also need to

498
00:50:25,215 --> 00:50:27,056
you know, publicly share my displeasure.

499
00:50:27,096 --> 00:50:28,216
And this isn't about you.

500
00:50:28,256 --> 00:50:30,998
This isn't about my team or all of us.

501
00:50:31,038 --> 00:50:32,438
I think we're doing the best what we can.

502
00:50:32,518 --> 00:50:39,181
And it's uncomfortable because like I said, my vote might not be different than someone else's vote and my vote might be different than someone else's.

503
00:50:39,221 --> 00:50:44,523
But ultimately, the person that's going to sit in that chair is going to look at us in a different light because of that.

504
00:50:44,584 --> 00:50:47,185
So whether we, it's human nature whether we like it or not.

505
00:50:47,205 --> 00:50:47,385
So, yeah.

506
00:50:47,405 --> 00:50:48,765
All right.

507
00:50:49,105 --> 00:50:49,566
Move forward?

508
00:50:50,006 --> 00:50:50,186
Yep.

509
00:50:51,386 --> 00:50:52,287
Is there a motion?

510
00:50:53,708 --> 00:50:54,608
Councilor Callahan?

511
00:50:56,281 --> 00:51:05,745
I move that we offer the city clerk position to the person who gets the most votes tonight.

512
00:51:06,445 --> 00:51:06,786
All right.

513
00:51:08,826 --> 00:51:09,527
As we call the roll.

514
00:51:10,587 --> 00:51:15,929
Let's just say, let's go around and say a name and then we'll make a motion to nominate that person.

515
00:51:16,049 --> 00:51:16,970
So if everyone would.

516
00:51:21,230 --> 00:51:32,735
We'll go up in the order of a roll call if everyone would please state the finalist that they would like to see moved forward and offered the position of City Clerk of the City of Medford.

517
00:51:34,696 --> 00:51:36,377
And I'll recognize you.

518
00:51:42,159 --> 00:51:43,500
In whatever order you press your buttons.

519
00:51:44,660 --> 00:51:46,101
Shall I go since my button's already pressed?

520
00:51:46,141 --> 00:51:46,341
Sure.

521
00:51:46,621 --> 00:51:47,361
Okay.

522
00:51:47,661 --> 00:51:48,442
Laurel Siegel.

523
00:51:48,842 --> 00:51:49,022
Great.

524
00:51:52,240 --> 00:51:54,561
Could you guys signal in and say a name?

525
00:51:57,363 --> 00:51:57,883
Councilor Malayne.

526
00:51:58,864 --> 00:51:59,604
Laurel Siegel.

527
00:51:59,945 --> 00:52:00,125
All right.

528
00:52:00,705 --> 00:52:01,846
Council Vice President Lazaro.

529
00:52:02,386 --> 00:52:03,026
Laurel Siegel.

530
00:52:04,367 --> 00:52:05,208
Councilor Scarpelli.

531
00:52:05,808 --> 00:52:06,368
Kevin Foley.

532
00:52:07,349 --> 00:52:08,130
Councilor Sang.

533
00:52:08,830 --> 00:52:09,470
Laurel Siegel.

534
00:52:09,911 --> 00:52:10,611
Councilor Lemming.

535
00:52:11,532 --> 00:52:12,192
Laurel Siegel.

536
00:52:12,212 --> 00:52:13,833
All right.

537
00:52:16,615 --> 00:52:17,475
Will someone make a motion?

538
00:52:17,595 --> 00:52:19,696
Laurel Siegel had a majority there.

539
00:52:19,997 --> 00:52:20,557
Is there a motion?

540
00:52:22,314 --> 00:52:25,957
Councilor Callahan on the motion to recommend Laurel Seagull to be offered the position of City Clerk.

541
00:52:25,997 --> 00:52:26,337
So moved.

542
00:52:26,858 --> 00:52:27,058
All right.

543
00:52:27,358 --> 00:52:30,881
On Councilor Callahan's motion, seconded by Councilor Scarpelli.

544
00:52:31,642 --> 00:52:32,943
Mr. Clerk, if you could please call the roll.

545
00:52:37,266 --> 00:52:38,047
Councilor Callahan?

546
00:52:38,347 --> 00:52:38,507
Yes.

547
00:52:39,568 --> 00:52:40,209
Councilor Lemming?

548
00:52:41,009 --> 00:52:41,289
Yes.

549
00:52:42,671 --> 00:52:43,251
Councilor Mullain?

550
00:52:43,271 --> 00:52:43,331
Yes.

551
00:52:44,792 --> 00:52:45,713
Councilor Scarpelli?

552
00:52:45,893 --> 00:52:46,033
Yes.

553
00:52:47,234 --> 00:52:47,915
Councilor Sang?

554
00:52:48,035 --> 00:52:48,175
Yes.

555
00:52:49,436 --> 00:52:50,357
Vice President Lazaro?

556
00:52:51,614 --> 00:52:52,435
and President Beers.

557
00:52:52,675 --> 00:52:52,935
Yes.

558
00:52:54,876 --> 00:52:57,077
Seven in the affirmative, none in the negative, the motion passes.

559
00:52:57,217 --> 00:53:12,827
Before we adjourn this meeting, I want to say one more thing which is I want to thank Acting Clerk Rich Alicio for his consummate professional service to the City of Medford as the Acting City Clerk over the last 10 plus months.

560
00:53:12,847 --> 00:53:17,389
Well, he's been acting since January but really functioning as our Acting City Clerk for even months before that.

561
00:53:19,088 --> 00:53:29,630
And I think under difficult decisions, difficult conditions and not enough staff in the office, you have done an incredible job.

562
00:53:29,670 --> 00:53:36,211
I think you've served as a consummate professional and especially I appreciate your continued service to the city of Medford.

563
00:53:36,912 --> 00:53:43,173
And as this offer process moves forward, you know, your continued service as our acting city clerk.

564
00:53:43,753 --> 00:53:44,593
So I wanted to thank you.

565
00:53:46,934 --> 00:53:47,154
All right.

566
00:53:48,074 --> 00:53:48,534
Is there a motion?

567
00:53:51,630 --> 00:53:53,351
Councillor Singh.

568
00:53:54,071 --> 00:53:58,134
I think I want to really thank you, Rich, for everything.

569
00:54:00,015 --> 00:54:05,118
It's difficult for us to be having this, to be in this moment.

570
00:54:06,559 --> 00:54:13,203
I don't think the public realizes the amount of adversity that you've faced in your role as acting clerk.

571
00:54:14,810 --> 00:54:19,733
And yet, you're so enthusiastic about making your job better.

572
00:54:20,453 --> 00:54:42,463
I've been especially impressed and I've been telling people, I've been especially impressed that recently, right, we have some motions or some papers and you come up to us after meetings just saying how you think your office could help in that process and how your office could, you know, contribute to policymaking ordinances from your experience working in the office.

573
00:54:43,170 --> 00:54:51,974
That perspective and the enthusiasm and proactiveness is something I see and I recognize and I want you to know that I see that.

574
00:54:54,675 --> 00:54:55,296
Thank you.

575
00:54:55,316 --> 00:54:55,536
Thank you.

576
00:54:55,576 --> 00:54:56,856
Councilor Scarbelli.

577
00:54:56,876 --> 00:54:57,677
Thank you, Mr. President.

578
00:54:57,697 --> 00:54:59,878
Again, to follow my, to be redundant.

579
00:55:01,384 --> 00:55:10,491
I think that some of the things we can and can't say about this process, unfortunately, affects Mr. Lazio.

580
00:55:10,571 --> 00:55:18,016
I think that what you've done, you've stepped into a very uncomfortable position and you've handled it with grace and honor.

581
00:55:18,036 --> 00:55:19,637
I think you've done a great job for us.

582
00:55:20,278 --> 00:55:22,319
I think that you are a true professional.

583
00:55:22,880 --> 00:55:28,063
I think that anytime I had an issue, Rich, you'd call me back within 15 minutes.

584
00:55:29,329 --> 00:55:33,292
And if you didn't have the answer, you did the due diligence to make sure you had the answer.

585
00:55:33,312 --> 00:55:38,296
I know that you've been under fire and you stood above it.

586
00:55:40,097 --> 00:55:43,180
And that's difficult because that showed your loyalty to this group.

587
00:55:43,720 --> 00:55:48,604
And I think, hope we never forget that because you did a great job.

588
00:55:48,884 --> 00:55:50,826
And I want everybody to know that publicly.

589
00:55:51,126 --> 00:55:53,648
And not to say my other colleagues don't feel the same way,

590
00:55:55,421 --> 00:56:09,391
you know, someone that isn't as articulate as most of my fellow colleagues when I send over a resolution and you'd call me and you'd say, Georgia, would you like me to correct the grammatical mistake or something simple as that so I don't look like a fool in a public forum.

591
00:56:09,631 --> 00:56:19,338
And it's stuff like that that I'd publicly say that thank you for being that safety net and we appreciate you more than you would know.

592
00:56:19,438 --> 00:56:20,199
So, thank you.

593
00:56:20,599 --> 00:56:21,159
Thank you.

594
00:56:21,179 --> 00:56:21,480
I appreciate it.

595
00:56:21,900 --> 00:56:22,280
Thank you.

596
00:56:22,520 --> 00:56:23,221
Councilor Callahan.

597
00:56:24,299 --> 00:56:34,302
In addition to the second, third, and fourth thing, what my colleagues have said, I also want to say that I'm, you know, very glad that you will be continuing with us.

598
00:56:34,682 --> 00:56:38,443
I don't want people in the public to think that, you know, you are leaving.

599
00:56:39,884 --> 00:56:45,465
But, you know, having your consistency in the office is going to be incredibly helpful as we move through this process.

600
00:56:46,506 --> 00:56:51,607
So in addition to all the gratitude and the, you know, thanks, I just wanted to say that as well.

601
00:56:55,597 --> 00:56:56,557
Vice President Lazaro.

602
00:56:58,178 --> 00:57:00,338
Rich I said this to you recently.

603
00:57:00,358 --> 00:57:02,219
I'm going to say it again publicly.

604
00:57:02,239 --> 00:57:07,920
I don't tell lies and if I do I don't do a very good job of it.

605
00:57:09,441 --> 00:57:14,882
And I look forward to continuing to not blow smoke anywhere in your vicinity.

606
00:57:16,563 --> 00:57:18,163
Thank you for being a bro.

607
00:57:18,744 --> 00:57:22,405
And I look forward to continue continuing to work with you.

608
00:57:23,645 --> 00:57:23,885
Thank you.

609
00:57:25,823 --> 00:57:26,263
Thank you.

610
00:57:26,763 --> 00:57:27,024
All right.

611
00:57:27,464 --> 00:57:28,064
Is there a motion?

612
00:57:32,766 --> 00:57:33,446
Councilor Lazaro.

613
00:57:33,706 --> 00:57:34,387
Oh, Councilor Callahan.

614
00:57:34,587 --> 00:57:38,748
A motion to adjourn by Councilor Callahan, seconded by Vice President Lazaro.

615
00:57:39,929 --> 00:57:46,312
Once the Committee of the Whole is adjourned, we'll get the regular meeting set up, and then we'll go from there, and there's about 20 items on the agenda, so we'll do our best.

616
00:57:47,092 --> 00:57:47,452
All right.

617
00:57:47,892 --> 00:57:50,313
Mr. Clerk, please call the roll on the motion to adjourn the Committee of the Whole.

618
00:57:50,793 --> 00:57:51,594
Councilor Callahan.

619
00:57:52,874 --> 00:57:53,575
Councilor Lemming.

620
00:57:54,255 --> 00:57:54,475
Yes.

621
00:57:55,916 --> 00:57:56,396
Councilor Malauulu?

622
00:57:56,416 --> 00:57:56,476
Yes.

623
00:57:57,937 --> 00:57:58,777
Councilor Scott Pelly?

624
00:57:59,318 --> 00:57:59,478
Yes.

625
00:58:00,158 --> 00:58:00,718
Councilor Hussain?

626
00:58:00,738 --> 00:58:02,019
Yes.

627
00:58:02,039 --> 00:58:02,959
Vice President Lazaro?

628
00:58:03,740 --> 00:58:04,480
And President Pierce?

629
00:58:04,720 --> 00:58:04,900
Yes.

630
00:58:04,920 --> 00:58:06,081
I move the affirmative, none the negative.

631
00:58:06,101 --> 00:58:06,881
The motion passes.

632
00:58:06,921 --> 00:58:10,583
Committee of the whole is adjourned and we will start the regular meeting in five minutes.

